{"id":"1405.4555","submitter":"Alexander Milov M","authors":"Sourav Tarafdar, Zvi Citron and Alexander Milov","title":"A Centrality Detector Concept","comments":"19 pages, 11 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/j.nima.2014.09.060","report-no":null,"categories":"nucl-ex","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The nucleus-nucleus impact parameter and collision geometry of a heavy ion\ncollision are typically characterized by assigning a collision \"centrality\". In\nall present heavy ion experiments centrality is measured indirectly, by\ndetecting the number of particles or the energy of the particles produced in\nthe interactions, typically at high rapidity. Centrality parameters are\nassociated to the measured detector response using the Glauber model. This\napproach suffers from systematic uncertainties related to the assumptions about\nthe particle production mechanism and limitations of the Glauber model. In the\ncollider based experiments there is a unique possibility to measure centrality\nparameters by registering spectator fragments remaining from the collision.\nThis approach does not require model assumptions and relies on the fact that\nspectators and participants are related via the total number of nucleons in the\ncolliding species. This article describes the concept of the centrality\ndetector for heavy ion experiment, which measures the total mass number of all\nfragments by measuring their deflection in the magnetic field of the collider\nelements.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 18 May 2014 21:26:04 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 7 Jun 2014 01:19:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-19"}
